80.7	Rupert_Sheldrake	Rupert Sheldrake	Alfred Rupert Sheldrake (born 28 June 1942) is an English scientist and author. He is known for having proposed a scientifically unorthodox account of morphogenesis and for his research into parapsychology. His books and papers stem from his theory of morphic resonance, and cover topics such as animal and plant development and behaviour, memory, telepathy, perception and cognition in general. His publications include A New Science of Life (1981), Seven Experiments That Could Change the World (1995), Dogs That Know When Their Owners Are Coming Home (1999), and The Sense of Being Stared At (2003), The Science Delusion: Freeing the spirit of enquiry (2012).	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/RupertSheldrake.jpg/150px-RupertSheldrake.jpg
